<DOC><DOCNO> AP900419-0204 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-90 1240EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-EmbassyHotels     04-19 0191</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Embassy Hotels,0198</SECOND><HEAD>Allied-Lyons Sells 41 Embassy Hotels to Jarvis</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Allied-Lyons PLC, the British liquor and foodcompany, said Thursday it was selling its Embassy Hotels chain toJarvis Hotels Ltd. for $331 million.   The sale of the chain, which operates 41 hotels in Britain,depends on Jarvis completing financing for the deal, Allied-Lyonssaid.   Jarvis is a newly formed hotel group headed by former HiltonInternational Chairman and Chief Executive John Jarvis. Jarvis willpay for Embassy Hotels with cash and debt, Allied-Lyons said.   Allied-Lyons said the sale was in line with its plans to developits core operations, and that the proceeds would help reduce itsdebt.   Late last year, Allied-Lyons paid $325 million for the U.S.doughnuts and coffee chain Dunkin Donuts Inc. and $894 million forthe liquor division of Whitbread and Co. PLC, a British brewinggroup.   Embassy reported a trading profit of $15.4 million on sales of$94 million in the year ended March 1989. Trading profit is profitbefore taxes and other items.   Allied-Lyons posted a trading profit of $964 million on sales of$7 billion in the same period.</TEXT></DOC>